# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-flink-sql
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink provides a high-throughput, low-latency streaming engine as well as support for event-time processing and state management.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink applications are fault-tolerant in the event of machine failure and support exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Programs can be written in Java, Python, and SQL and are automatically compiled and optimized into dataflow programs that are executed in a cluster or cloud environment.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink does not provide its own data-storage system, but provides data-source and sink connectors to systems such as Apache Doris, Amazon Kinesis, Apache Kafka, HDFS, Apache Cassandra, and ElasticSearch.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Apache Flink is developed under the Apache License 2.0 by the Apache Flink Community within the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The project is driven by 127 committers and over 1354 contributors.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Apache Flink's dataflow programming model provides event-at-a-time processing on both finite and infinite datasets.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Apache Flink includes two core APIs: a DataStream API for bounded or unbounded streams of data and a DataSet API for bounded data sets.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink also offers a Table API, which is a SQL-like expression language for relational stream and batch processing that can be easily embedded in Flink's DataStream and DataSet APIs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The highest-level language supported by Flink is SQL, which is semantically similar to the Table API and represents programs as SQL query expressions.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Upon execution, Flink programs are mapped to streaming dataflows.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Every Flink dataflow starts with one or more sources (a data input, e.g., a message queue or a file system) and ends with one or more sinks (a data output, e.g., a message queue, file system, or database).
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] An arbitrary number of transformations can be performed on the stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] These streams can be arranged as a directed, acyclic dataflow graph, allowing an application to branch and merge dataflows.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink offers ready-built source and sink connectors with Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, HDFS, Apache Cassandra, and more.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink programs run as a distributed system within a cluster and can be deployed in a standalone mode as well as on YARN, Mesos, Docker-based setups along with other resource management frameworks.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Apache Flink includes a lightweight fault tolerance mechanism based on distributed checkpoints.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] A checkpoint is an automatic, asynchronous snapshot of the state of an application and the position in a source stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In the case of a failure, a Flink program with checkpointing enabled will, upon recovery, resume processing from the last completed checkpoint, ensuring that Flink maintains exactly-once state semantics within an application.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The checkpointing mechanism exposes hooks for application code to include external systems into the checkpointing mechanism as well (like opening and committing transactions with a database system).
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink also includes a mechanism called savepoints, which are manually-triggered checkpoints.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] A user can generate a savepoint, stop a running Flink program, then resume the program from the same application state and position in the stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Savepoints enable updates to a Flink program or a Flink cluster without losing the application's state .
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] As of Flink 1.2, savepoints also allow to restart an application with a different parallelism—allowing users to adapt to changing workloads.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink's DataStream API enables transformations (e.g. filters, aggregations, window functions) on bounded or unbounded streams of data.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The DataStream API includes more than 20 different types of transformations and is available in Java and Scala.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Apache Beam “provides an advanced unified programming model, allowing (a developer) to implement batch and streaming data processing jobs that can run on any execution engine.” The Apache Flink-on-Beam runner is the most feature-rich according to a capability matrix maintained by the Beam community.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] data Artisans, in conjunction with the Apache Flink community, worked closely with the Beam community to develop a Flink runner.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink's DataSet API enables transformations (e.g., filters, mapping, joining, grouping) on bounded datasets.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The DataSet API includes more than 20 different types of transformations.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The API is available in Java, Scala and an experimental Python API.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink's DataSet API is conceptually similar to the DataStream API.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink's Table API is a SQL-like expression language for relational stream and batch processing that can be embedded in Flink's Java and Scala DataSet and DataStream APIs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The Table API and SQL interface operate on a relational Table abstraction.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Tables can be created from external data sources or from existing DataStreams and DataSets.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The Table API supports relational operators such as selection, aggregation, and joins on Tables.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Tables can also be queried with regular SQL.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The Table API and SQL offer equivalent functionality and can be mixed in the same program.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] When a Table is converted back into a DataSet or DataStream, the logical plan, which was defined by relational operators and SQL queries, is optimized using Apache Calcite and is transformed into a DataSet or DataStream program.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink Forward is an annual conference about Apache Flink.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The first edition of Flink Forward took place in 2015 in Berlin.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The two-day conference had over 250 attendees from 16 countries.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Sessions were organized in two tracks with over 30 technical presentations from Flink developers and one additional track with hands-on Flink training.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In 2016, 350 participants joined the conference and over 40 speakers presented technical talks in 3 parallel tracks.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] On the third day, attendees were invited to participate in hands-on training sessions.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In 2017, the event expanded to San Francisco, as well.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The conference day was dedicated to technical talks on how Flink is used in the enterprise, Flink system internals, ecosystem integrations with Flink, and the future of the platform.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] It featured keynotes, talks from Flink users in industry and academia, and hands-on training sessions on Apache Flink.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In 2020, following the COVID-19 pandemic, Flink Forward's spring edition which was supposed to be hosted in San Francisco was canceled.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Instead, the conference was hosted virtually, starting on April 22 and concluding on April 24, featuring live keynotes, Flink use cases, Apache Flink internals, and other topics on stream processing and real-time analytics.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In 2024 Flink Forward returned to Berlin, its birth place, for the 10th anniversary.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The conference highlighted the new Flink 2.0 plans, where Java 8 is dropped and a new state backend is introduced.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink CDC was also introduced, allowing no code yaml authored flows.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] There was also a session on Flink's adoption of OpenLineage.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In 2010, the research project "Stratosphere: Information Management on the Cloud" led by Volker Markl (funded by the German Research Foundation (DFG)) was started as a collaboration of Technische Universität Berlin, Humboldt-Universität zu Berlin, and Hasso-Plattner-Institut Potsdam.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] Flink started from a fork of Stratosphere's distributed execution engine and it became an Apache Incubator project in March 2014.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] In December 2014, Flink was accepted as an Apache top-level project.
[src:apache-flink-sql/apache-flink] The 1.14.1, 1.13.4, 1.12.6, 1.11.5 releases, which were supposed to only contain a Log4j upgrade to 2.15.0, were skipped because CVE-2021-45046 was discovered during the release publication.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:apache-flink-sql/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] If you get stuck, check out our community support resources.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] In particular, Apache Flink’s user mailing list is consistently ranked as one of the most active of any Apache project, and is a great way to get help quickly.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] The reference documentation covers all the details.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] Before putting your Flink job into production, read the Production Readiness Checklist.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] For an overview of possible deployment targets, see Clusters and Deployments.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] Release notes cover important changes between Flink versions.
[src:apache-flink-sql/flink-docs-stable] Please read them carefully if you plan to upgrade your Flink setup.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:apache-flink-sql/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] While many operations in a dataflow simply look at one individual *event at a time* (for example an event parser), some operations remember information across multiple events (for example window operators).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] These operations are called **stateful**.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Flink needs to be aware of the state in order to make it fault tolerant using checkpoints and savepoints.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Knowledge about the state also allows for rescaling Flink applications, meaning that Flink takes care of redistributing state across parallel instances.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] When working with state, it might also be useful to read about Flink’s state backends.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Flink provides different state backends that specify how and where state is stored.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Keyed state is maintained in what can be thought of as an embedded key/value store.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The state is partitioned and distributed strictly together with the streams that are read by the stateful operators.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Hence, access to the key/value state is only possible on *keyed streams*, i.e. after a keyed/partitioned data exchange, and is restricted to the values associated with the current event’s key.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Aligning the keys of streams and state makes sure that all state updates are local operations, guaranteeing consistency without transaction overhead.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] This alignment also allows Flink to redistribute the state and adjust the stream partitioning transparently.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Keyed State is further organized into so-called *Key Groups*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Key Groups are the atomic unit by which Flink can redistribute Keyed State; there are exactly as many Key Groups as the defined maximum parallelism.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] During execution each parallel instance of a keyed operator works with the keys for one or more Key Groups.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Flink implements fault tolerance using a combination of **stream replay** and **checkpointing**.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] A checkpoint marks a specific point in each of the input streams along with the corresponding state for each of the operators.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] A streaming dataflow can be resumed from a checkpoint while maintaining consistency *(exactly-once processing semantics)* by restoring the state of the operators and replaying the records from the point of the checkpoint.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The checkpoint interval is a means of trading off the overhead of fault tolerance during execution with the recovery time (the number of records that need to be replayed).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The fault tolerance mechanism continuously draws snapshots of the distributed streaming data flow.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] For streaming applications with small state, these snapshots are very light-weight and can be drawn frequently without much impact on performance.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The state of the streaming applications is stored at a configurable place, usually in a distributed file system.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] In case of a program failure (due to machine-, network-, or software failure), Flink stops the distributed streaming dataflow.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The system then restarts the operators and resets them to the latest successful checkpoint.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The input streams are reset to the point of the state snapshot.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Any records that are processed as part of the restarted parallel dataflow are guaranteed to not have affected the previously checkpointed state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The central part of Flink’s fault tolerance mechanism is drawing consistent snapshots of the distributed data stream and operator state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] These snapshots act as consistent checkpoints to which the system can fall back in case of a failure.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Flink’s mechanism for drawing these snapshots is described in “Lightweight Asynchronous Snapshots for Distributed Dataflows”.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] It is inspired by the standard Chandy-Lamport algorithm for distributed snapshots and is specifically tailored to Flink’s execution model.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Keep in mind that everything to do with checkpointing can be done asynchronously.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The checkpoint barriers don’t travel in lock step and operations can asynchronously snapshot their state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Since Flink 1.11, checkpoints can be taken with or without alignment.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] In this section, we describe aligned checkpoints first.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] A core element in Flink’s distributed snapshotting are the *stream barriers*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] These barriers are injected into the data stream and flow with the records as part of the data stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Barriers never overtake records, they flow strictly in line.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] A barrier separates the records in the data stream into the set of records that goes into the current snapshot, and the records that go into the next snapshot.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Each barrier carries the ID of the snapshot whose records it pushed in front of it.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Barriers do not interrupt the flow of the stream and are hence very lightweight.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Multiple barriers from different snapshots can be in the stream at the same time, which means that various snapshots may happen concurrently.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Stream barriers are injected into the parallel data flow at the stream sources.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The point where the barriers for snapshot *n* are injected (let’s call it *Sn*) is the position in the source stream up to which the snapshot covers the data.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] For example, in Apache Kafka, this position would be the last record’s offset in the partition.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] This position *Sn* is reported to the *checkpoint coordinator* (Flink’s JobManager).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] When an intermediate operator has received a barrier for snapshot *n* from all of its input streams, it emits a barrier for snapshot *n* into all of its outgoing streams.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Once a sink operator (the end of a streaming DAG) has received the barrier *n* from all of its input streams, it acknowledges that snapshot *n* to the checkpoint coordinator.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] After all sinks have acknowledged a snapshot, it is considered completed.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Once snapshot *n* has been completed, the job will never again ask the source for records from before *Sn*, since at that point these records (and their descendant records) will have passed through the entire data flow topology.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Operators that receive more than one input stream need to *align* the input streams on the snapshot barriers.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Note that the alignment is needed for all operators with multiple inputs and for operators after a shuffle when they consume output streams of multiple upstream subtasks.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] When operators contain any form of *state*, this state must be part of the snapshots as well.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Operators snapshot their state at the point in time when they have received all snapshot barriers from their input streams, and before emitting the barriers to their output streams.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] At that point, all updates to the state from records before the barriers have been made, and no updates that depend on records from after the barriers have been applied.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Because the state of a snapshot may be large, it is stored in a configurable *state backend*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] By default, this is the JobManager’s memory, but for production use a distributed reliable storage should be configured (such as HDFS).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] After the state has been stored, the operator acknowledges the checkpoint, emits the snapshot barrier into the output streams, and proceeds.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Recovery under this mechanism is straightforward: Upon a failure, Flink selects the latest completed checkpoint *k*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The system then re-deploys the entire distributed dataflow, and gives each operator the state that was snapshotted as part of checkpoint *k*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The sources are set to start reading the stream from position *Sk*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] For example in Apache Kafka, that means telling the consumer to start fetching from offset *Sk*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] If state was snapshotted incrementally, the operators start with the state of the latest full snapshot and then apply a series of incremental snapshot updates to that state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] See Restart Strategies for more information.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Checkpointing can also be performed unaligned.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The basic idea is that checkpoints can overtake all in-flight data as long as the in-flight data becomes part of the operator state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Note that this approach is actually closer to the Chandy-Lamport algorithm , but Flink still inserts the barrier in the sources to avoid overloading the checkpoint coordinator.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Consequently, the operator only briefly stops the processing of input to mark the buffers, forwards the barrier, and creates the snapshot of the other state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Unaligned checkpointing ensures that barriers are arriving at the sink as fast as possible.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] It’s especially suited for applications with at least one slow moving data path, where alignment times can reach hours.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] However, since it’s adding additional I/O pressure, it doesn’t help when the I/O to the state backends is the bottleneck.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] See the more in-depth discussion in ops for other limitations.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Note that savepoints will always be aligned.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Operators first recover the in-flight data before starting processing any data from upstream operators in unaligned checkpointing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Aside from that, it performs the same steps as during recovery of aligned checkpoints.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The exact data structures in which the key/values indexes are stored depends on the chosen state backend.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] One state backend stores data in an in-memory hash map, another state backend uses RocksDB as the key/value store.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] In addition to defining the data structure that holds the state, the state backends also implement the logic to take a point-in-time snapshot of the key/value state and store that snapshot as part of a checkpoint.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] State backends can be configured without changing your application logic.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] All programs that use checkpointing can resume execution from a **savepoint**.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Savepoints allow both updating your programs and your Flink cluster without losing any state.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Savepoints are **manually triggered checkpoints**, which take a snapshot of the program and write it out to a state backend.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] They rely on the regular checkpointing mechanism for this.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Savepoints are similar to checkpoints except that they are **triggered by the user** and **don’t automatically expire** when newer checkpoints are completed.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] To make proper use of savepoints, it’s important to understand the differences between checkpoints and savepoints which is described in checkpoints vs. savepoints.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] The alignment step may add latency to the streaming program.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Usually, this extra latency is on the order of a few milliseconds, but we have seen cases where the latency of some outliers increased noticeably.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] For applications that require consistently super low latencies (few milliseconds) for all records, Flink has a switch to skip the stream alignment during a checkpoint.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Checkpoint snapshots are still drawn as soon as an operator has seen the checkpoint barrier from each input.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] When the alignment is skipped, an operator keeps processing all inputs, even after some checkpoint barriers for checkpoint *n* arrived.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] That way, the operator also processes elements that belong to checkpoint *n+1* before the state snapshot for checkpoint *n* was taken.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] On a restore, these records will occur as duplicates, because they are both included in the state snapshot of checkpoint *n*, and will be replayed as part of the data after checkpoint *n*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stateful-stream-processing] Flink executes batch programs as a special case of streaming programs in BATCH ExecutionMode , where the streams are bounded (finite number of elements).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:apache-flink-sql/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
